hat are outside<br />the scope of what sparse does.<br /><br />It would probably be good to disable things that are fundamentally<br />hard to fix, and aim for a clean sparse build, and maybe people would<br />start using it at least for user pointer checking where it really does<br />work.<br /><br />Of course, even there it depends on pointers _statically_ being user<br />pointers, but happily we do largely follow that rule. We've had a few<br />nasty cases where we have a pointer that is conditionally user or<br />kernel pointer, but they are thankfully pretty rare.<br /><br />                   Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
